Step 1: Identify the cash and cash equivalents.
• From the balance sheet, the "Cash on Hand" is –206636.07.
• "Bank Deposits" are 2406.99.
• Their sum equals –206636.07 + 2406.99 = –204229.08.
• (This also matches the “Ending Balance” on the Cash and Cash Equivalents in the cash flow statement.)

Step 2: Identify the total current liabilities.
• From the balance sheet, the "Total Current Liabilities" is 737762.05.

Step 3: Calculate the Cash to Current Debt Ratio.
• The ratio = Cash and Cash Equivalents / Total Current Liabilities.
• Ratio = (–204229.08) / (737762.05) ≈ –0.2771.

Step 4: Rounding to two decimal places gives –0.28.

Thus, the solution is:
